@node Filesystem Design Summary
@section Filesystem Design Summary

VibeOS does not implement a general mount tree.  Instead, it exposes two
read-only backends and a dispatcher:

@itemize @bullet
@item the initramfs backend for the root filesystem, and
@item the ext2 backend for @file{/usr}.
@end itemize

The VFS layer in @file{kernel/src/fs.c} decides which backend owns a path and
then forwards lookup and read operations accordingly.

@node Initramfs Backend
@section Initramfs Backend

The initramfs parser consumes a @code{cpio newc} archive.  It stores a flat
table of entries in memory:

@itemize @bullet
@item normalized path,
@item data pointer,
@item file size, and
@item mode bits.
@end itemize

Important implementation details:

@itemize @bullet
@item Up to 1024 entries are remembered.
@item Archives up to 16 MiB may be copied to a fixed address at
@code{0x30000000}.
@item Paths are normalized to absolute names.
@item Lookups are linear scans over the indexed entry table.
@end itemize

This backend is intentionally simple because the root image is built by the
VibeOS scripts and loaded as an immutable module.

@node ext2 Backend for /usr
@section ext2 Backend for /usr

The ext2 implementation is a read-only in-memory mount.

It supports:

@itemize @bullet
@item superblock parsing,
@item group descriptor parsing,
@item inode lookup,
@item direct, single-indirect, double-indirect, and triple-indirect data block
resolution,
@item regular file reads,
@item symlink reads,
@item directory scans, and
@item directory child collection for user-visible directory enumeration.
@end itemize

The ext2 backend only claims paths rooted at @file{/usr}.  A mounted ext2 image
therefore augments the root namespace without replacing it.

@node VFS Routing Rules
@section VFS Routing Rules

@findex fs_read
@findex fs_collect_children

The routing rule is intentionally small:

@itemize @bullet
@item If the ext2 image is mounted and the path belongs to @file{/usr}, use the
ext2 backend.
@item Otherwise use the initramfs backend.
@end itemize

This affects:

@itemize @bullet
@item path lookup,
@item file reads,
@item symlink reads, and
@item child enumeration.
@end itemize

The root directory behaves like a merged view.  It can expose initramfs entries
plus @file{/usr} when the ext2 backend is mounted.

@node Synthetic Directories and Devices
@section Synthetic Directories and Devices

The syscall layer synthesizes directory and device objects beyond what the
underlying backend filesystems contain.

Recognized synthetic directories include:

@example
/
/bin
/dev
/etc
/home
/proc
/sys
/tmp
/usr
/usr/bin
/var
@end example

Recognized synthetic non-directory paths include:

@example
/dev/tty
/dev/console
/dev/null
/dev/fb0
/proc/self/exe
@end example

These special paths are handled in the syscall layer, especially in the helper
functions around @code{path_mode_size}, @code{sys_openat}, @code{sys_ioctl}, and
@code{sys_readlinkat}.

@node Path Resolution and Symlink Semantics
@section Path Resolution and Symlink Semantics

Path resolution follows a predictable set of rules:

@itemize @bullet
@item relative paths are made absolute against either the current working
directory or a directory file descriptor,
@item repeated slashes are collapsed,
@item @samp{.} segments are ignored,
@item @samp{..} segments back up one component when possible, and
@item symlinks are resolved with a fixed maximum depth.
@end itemize

Final-component symlink following is selectable depending on the operation.  For
example, @code{readlinkat} does not follow the final link because it needs the
link object itself.

@node Read-Only Nature of the Filesystems
@section Read-Only Nature of the Filesystems

The shipped root initramfs and @file{/usr} mount are read-only in the current
boot configuration.

You can:

@itemize @bullet
@item open files,
@item read files,
@item stat files,
@item traverse directories,
@item read symlinks, and
@item access synthetic device-like paths.
@end itemize

The ext2 backend has read-write support for regular-file data, block and inode
allocation and freeing, truncate, file creation, special-file creation,
directories, symlinks, hard links, unlink, rmdir, rename, chmod, and chown.
Those paths are exposed through VFS helpers and Linux-compatible syscall
entry points, but the shipped @file{/usr} image is still mounted read-only, so
mutation attempts there fail with @code{EROFS}.
